      context: "This final lesson of Term 1 brings everything together. We have studied God's character — His creative power, His holiness, His love, His sovereignty, His Word. Now we confront the central question of the entire curriculum: will you obey? John 15:14 is one of the most intimate and challenging verses in Scripture. Jesus does not say 'You are my friends if you attend church' or 'if you feel emotional about me' or 'if you know theology.' He says: 'Ye are my friends, if ye do whatsoever I command you.' Friendship with Jesus is defined by obedience. 1 Samuel 15:22-23 reinforces this: 'Behold, to obey is better than sacrifice, and to hearken than the fat of rams. For rebellion is as the sin of witchcraft.' King Saul had disobeyed God while performing religious activities — he kept the best animals from the Amalekites for sacrifice instead of destroying everything as God commanded. He substituted his own religious ideas for God's clear command. Samuel's response is devastating: God does not want your worship if you will not give Him your obedience. James 1:22-25 completes the picture: 'Be ye doers of the word, and not hearers only, deceiving your own selves.' A person who hears the Word but does not obey it is like someone who looks in a mirror, sees their face, and immediately forgets what they look like. Hearing without doing is self-deception.",
